   <mods:abstract>Is pleased with the observations of Murray's friend. The lawfulness of the
            invasion and conquest of Canaan is indubitable; does not decide the question whether any
            wars unless under divine command are permitted by moral law. Wars before and after the
            time of Moses are recorded without reproof. It is not clear that the theocracy admitted
            only those wars commanded by the Almighty. When arguments in favor of just and necessary
            war are proved fallacious he shall think and act accordingly. The extract from William
            Penn forms a useful tract in its declaration that the Scriptures were given by men of
            God moved by the Holy Spirit. This is also inculcated in the address of the trustees of
            the African Schools. Asks after Murray's brother.</mods:abstract>
